diterranean Islandness from Ancient to Early Modern Times: A Philological Approach -- tMarseille and the Mediterranean in the Writings of Yoko Tawada and Tahar Ben Jelloun -- tHeterotopic and Striated Spaces in the Mediterranean Crime Fiction of Amara Lakhous and Jean-Claude Izzo -- tPart IV: Conceptional Spaces -- tA Mediterranean Utopia. The Renaissance Fiction of Plusiapolis as an Ideal of Mediterranean Connectivity -- tThe pensée de midi Revisited: Mediterranean Connectivity Between Paul Arène, Albert Camus, and Louis Brauquier -- tThe Possibility of the Mediterranean and the Contribution of Poetic Cross-Cultural Philologies During the Twentieth Century. Al-Andalus in the Poetry of Federico García Lorca, Louis Aragon, and Maḥmūd Darwiš -- tĎurišin's Interliterary Mediterranean as a Model for World Literature -- tA Female Mediterranean South? Italian Women Writers Gendering Spaces of Meridione: Nadia Terranova's Farewell ghosts (2018) -- tLearning from the Sea: Migration and Maritime Archives -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex nominum0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aMediterranean studies flourish in literary and cultural studies, but concepts of the Mediterranean and the theories and methods they use are very disparate. This is because the Mediterranean is not a simple geographical or historical unity, but a multiplicity, a network of highly interconnected elements, each of which is different and individual. Talking about Mediterranean literature raises the question of whether the connectivity of Mediterranean literature can or should be limited in some way by constructing an inside and an outside of the Mediterranean. What kind of connectivity and fragmentation do literary texts produce, how do they build and interrupt references (to the real, to fictional forms of representation, to history, but also to other texts and discourses), how do they create and deny communication, and how do they engage with and reflect literary and non-literary concepts of the Mediterranean? These and other questions are considered and discussed in the over twenty contributions gathered in this volume.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aIdentität. 4aKulturgeschichte. 4aMittelmeer-Studien. 4aVergleichende Literaturwissenschaft. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aComparative Literary Studies.  aCultural History.  aIdentity.  aMediterranean Studies.1 aArslan, C. Ceyhun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaquey, Stéphane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenussi, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeganutti, Marianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbermeier, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabris, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabris, Angela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrima, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGöschl, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGöschl, Albert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHock, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIzzo, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJöhnk, Marília, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKefalidou, Charikleia Magdalini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id